===========================================================
          THE BACKROOM - PROJECT ARCHITECTURE & FLOW
===========================================================

1. DATABASE CONNECTION (AIVEN CLOUD)
------------------------------------
* Master Account: We use ONE main Service Account (***REMOVED***).
* Why only ONE?
  - PERFORMANCE: Opening new MySQL accounts for every user
    is slow and uses too many resources.
  - CONTROL: We don't want users having direct access to
    the DB engine. Only the Java App has the "Master Key."
* Security: Use a 'db.properties' file in resources.
* Portability: Anyone with the zip file can run the app
  without setting up their own MySQL users in Aiven.

2. USERS TABLE (Run this in Aiven Console)
-------------------------------------------------
* Why a Table Schema instead of SQL accounts?
  - LIMITATIONS: Aiven limits total DB users. A table can
    hold millions of rows/users without crashing.
  - FLEXIBILITY: We can add columns like 'profile_pic' or
    'join_date' easily. You can't do that with SQL accounts.

3. APPLICATION USER FLOW
-------------------------
A. GUEST MODE (Default):
   - User opens app -> Auto-logs into 'guest_user' account.
   - Logic: if (user.role == GUEST), disable "Add", "Edit".

B. SIGN UP / LOGIN:
   - Sign Up: Saves new user as 'MEMBER'.
   - Login: Checks 'users' table.
   - Role-Based Access: Java logic handles who sees what.

C. REMEMBER ME:
   - Store 'username' in 'remember.properties'.
   - SECURITY: NEVER store the raw password in text files!

4. THE "HALA" PREVENTION RULES
-------------------------------
* Logic over SQL: We use IF statements in Java to restrict
  users. Even if they click a button, the DAO should check
  their ROLE before running the query.
* Error Handling: All DB methods must throw exceptions to
  the UI so we can show Alerts to the user.

